sources.title: Articles on Smashing Magazine — For Web Designers And Developers

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Temani Afif)
articles.description: The CSS `border-image` property is one of those properties you undoubtedly know exists but may not have ever reached for. In this article, Temani Afif demonstrates different approaches for using `border-image` to create clever decorative accents and shapes.
articles.title: The Complex But Awesome CSS border-image Property

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Louis Lazaris)
articles.description: Useful front-end tools for CSS and JavaScript developers that were most popular last year and will help you speed up your development workflow. Let’s dive in!
articles.title: Top Front-End Tools Of 2023

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Atila Fassina)
articles.description: Are you ready for a little exercise of pulling a framework apart and putting the pieces back together? In this article, Atila Fassina explains how meta-frameworks have evolved around core libraries in their own unique ways.
articles.title: SolidStart: A Different Breed Of Meta-Framework

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Adrian Bece)
articles.description: The View Transitions API is a new — but game-changing — feature that allows us to do the types of reactive state-based UI and page transitions that have traditionally been exclusive to JavaScript frameworks. In the second half of this mini two-part series, Adrian Bece expands on the demos from the first article to demonstrate how the View Transitions API can be used to transition not just elements between two states but the transition between full views and pages in single-page and multi-page applications.
articles.title: The View Transitions API And Delightful UI Animations (Part 2)

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Cosima Mielke)
articles.description: Let’s start into the new year with a little inspiration boost: wallpapers created with love by the community for the community. Happy 2024!
articles.title: The Magic Of New Beginnings (January 2024 Wallpapers Edition)

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Juan Diego Rodríguez)
articles.description: JavaScript may be the most popular client-side language in the world, but it’s far from perfect and not without its quirks. Juan Diego Rodriguez examines several “absurd” JavaScript eccentricities and explains how they made it into the language as well as how to avoid them in your own code.
articles.title: Making Sense Of “Senseless” JavaScript Features

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Adrian Bece)
articles.description: The View Transitions API is a new — but game-changing — feature that allows us to do the types of reactive state-based UI and page transitions that have traditionally been exclusive to JavaScript frameworks. In the first part of this mini two-part series, Adrian Bece thoroughly explains why we need the API and demonstrates its basic usage.
articles.title: The View Transitions API And Delightful UI Animations (Part 1)

mosh (“mobile shell”) is a remote shell for intermittent connections.
the network stack of Wechat is reputed to be robust to network shenanigans: mars, .
Prefer file-sync over uploading
Downloading big files if you must
CLI
This was my repeated-timeout download command:
function wget_non_california () { until wget -c --timeout=10 $*; do sleep 10; done }
ChatGPT recommends the followng wget options to robustly download:
wget --load-cookies=/path/to/cookies.txt --continue --timeout=30 --tries=0 http://example.com/file
That --load-cookies bit assumes that we want to download things using a browser session.
For that we would need a browser extions cookies.txt
Downthemall
DownThemAll! has a more robust download system, and supports Firefox, Chrome and Edge
macOS with bad internet
Switching wifi off and on again helps.
(detailed version.)
Turn wifi on or off from the macOS terminal command line:
networksetup -setairportpower en0 off
networksetup -setairportpower en0 on
Flaky finder
I don’t know why this happens, but this is one of the many nasty side-effects of unreliable network connections is Finder flaking out.
If your nasty ISP drops enough packets there are a whole bunch of ways that your Mac computer will DOS itself into the ground, because low bandwidth is a state alien to Apple engineers.
Here are some potential workarounds:
Look for misbehaving processes
and corrupt wassamajiggies.
Or tell Finder to stop obsessing about
fancy network drives that won’t work anyway:
sudo vi /etc/auto_master
In this file comment out /net.
Now,
sudo automount -vc

Placeholder, for discussing the Taylor expansion equivalent for an SDE.

Let \(f\) denote a smooth function. Then, using Itô’s lemma, we may construct a local approximation by
\[
f\left(X_{t}\right)=f\left(X_{0}\right)+\int_{s=0}^{t} L^{0} f\left(X_{s}\right) d s+\int_{s=0}^{t} L^{1} f\left(X_{s}\right) d B_{s}
\]
where the operators \(L^{0}\) and \(L^{1}\) are defined by
\[
L^{0}=a(x) \frac{\partial}{\partial x}+\frac{1}{2} b(x)^{2} \frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x^{2}} \quad \text { and } \quad L^{1}=b(x) \frac{\partial}{\partial x}
\]
We may notionally repeat this procedure arbitrarily many times to take into account higher-order derivatives of the function \(f\).
Each repetition produces a higher order of Itô-Taylor expansion.

A term coined by Jung (Jung 1923).
Depue and Fu (2013) mentions its durability as a psychometric concept into the modern era:
Extraversion represents a higher-order personality trait that has been identified in virtually all classificatory systems of the structure of personality, including Eysenck and Gray's models (Gray 1994), the Five-Factor model (Costa Jr. and McCrae 2000), Tellegen's Multidimensional Personality Questionnaire (MPQ) model (Tellegen and Waller 2008), and Zuckerman's Alternative Five-Factor model (Zuckerman 2002). Dynamic equity split models
